cs.SI, cs.SD, cs.SOC, cs.CYBER, cs.HC 

This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as it investigates the collective behavior of online social networking communities. It may also belong to cs.SD (Software Development and Programming) as it involves the analysis of a large dataset of tweets. Additionally, it could be categorized under cs.SOC (Computational Social Science) as it explores the social mechanisms that cause assortative mixing in online social networks. It may also be relevant to cs.CYBER (Cybersecurity and Privacy) as it touches on the spread of positive and negative sentiments through human society. Finally, it could be classified under cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) as it considers how online networks modulate human collective mood states.
